We thought since FY23 is nearly over, we will extend it to six years that way.

60
00:03:43,801 --> 00:03:44,714
it would be a complete plan.

61
00:03:48,761 --> 00:03:52,602
So just by way of introduction, I want to introduce myself and the Collins Center.

62
00:03:53,042 --> 00:04:02,066
So as the Council President said, my name is Sarah Concanon, and I am the Director of Municipal Services at the Collins Center for Public Management at UMass Boston.

63
00:04:02,586 --> 00:04:15,130
The Collins Center was established in 2008 by the state legislature at UMass Boston to provide affordable and practical consulting and technical assistance to cities and towns around the Commonwealth.

64
00:04:15,490 --> 00:04:23,600
We also work with regional governments, school districts, state agencies, and any other public sector entity that is in furtherance of our mission.

65
00:04:26,352 --> 00:04:36,838
Two years ago, the city of Medford worked with me to receive a grant through the Community Compact Best Practices Program to develop a capital improvement plan.

66
00:04:38,779 --> 00:04:44,983
A year ago, the mayor asked me to come back and help her and her administration

67
00:04:45,943 --> 00:04:49,525
update the plan with the department heads.

68
00:04:50,025 --> 00:04:57,868
And so what I've been doing for the past year is sort of managing the process so that we can get to an updated capital plan.

69
00:05:00,409 --> 00:05:06,772
I want to just briefly for anybody who's watching who isn't familiar, just go through a few definitions.

70
00:05:06,852 --> 00:05:12,614
I mean, I know the counselors know this, but what is a capital project and what is a capital improvement plan?

71
00:05:13,214 --> 00:05:22,478
So a capital project is typically a major non-recurring expense with a cost of at least $10,000 and a useful life of at least five years.

72
00:05:23,058 --> 00:05:35,973
The $10,000 threshold is a little bit low for a city of Medford size, but nonetheless, we thought using a lower threshold would make sense because we didn't want any projects that were in the $10,000, $20,000 range to get lost.

73
00:05:37,315 --> 00:05:40,279
So that is how we define a capital project.

74
00:05:41,624 --> 00:05:50,531
A capital improvement plan is a multi-year plan that is comprehensive in the sense that it covers all funding sources and all departments in the city.

75
00:05:51,032 --> 00:05:52,793
And it's also financially viable.

76
00:05:53,274 --> 00:05:58,618
So this is something that the call-in center really pushes our clients to think about.

77
00:05:58,938 --> 00:06:07,526
What we don't wanna do is spend a year developing a wishlist that will never be funded because that's not really the purpose of a plan.

78
00:06:07,806 --> 00:06:10,288
The plan is supposed to be there so that residents can know

79
00:06:10,748 --> 00:06:16,371
and expect that there's going to be certain investments in their schools, in their roads, in their water system.

80
00:06:16,891 --> 00:06:26,416
It also exists so that the finance team in the city can make appropriate decisions about issuing debt, about revenue, and about the operating budget, and so on.

81
00:06:26,936 --> 00:06:33,380
And so it's really important that that third bullet is achieved when you're going through a capital improvement planning process.

82
00:06:33,960 --> 00:06:37,622
If you don't achieve that, it's really not a plan, it's simply a wish list.

83
00:06:43,828 --> 00:06:54,831
Again, for any members of the public who might be learning about a CIP for the first time tonight, it's a really important document and it's an important process for a city or town to go through.

84
00:06:55,271 --> 00:06:59,012
If you don't have a capital plan, there are a lot of things that can go wrong.

85
00:06:59,472 --> 00:07:03,493
So for example, there could be negative impacts to public health or public safety.

86
00:07:04,393 --> 00:07:11,435
I think about, for example, an intersection that is not well-designed or maybe has not been updated in many, many decades.

87
00:07:11,715 --> 00:07:13,096
It could be a public safety issue.

88
00:07:13,196 --> 00:07:21,200
And so making sure that you get those types of projects on your list that are going to improve public health, improve public safety is important.

89
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:24,641
There's also a certain degree of exposure to legal liability.

90
00:07:24,701 --> 00:07:34,566
If you're not investing in your facilities, if you have roads and sidewalks and facilities that are in disrepair, it could expose the city to legal liability.

91
00:07:35,790 --> 00:07:38,673
It could also create staff inefficiency and ineffectiveness.

92
00:07:39,654 --> 00:07:46,700
The best example that we hear all the time at the call-in center when we work with our clients is about vehicles.

93
00:07:47,221 --> 00:07:54,407
You know, public works staff are out in the field on the day-to-day and if they don't have vehicles that can work that

94
00:07:55,288 --> 00:08:01,615
can offer heating and cooling and aren't in the shop, then that makes them really inefficient.

95
00:08:02,035 --> 00:08:16,912
And so it's important to make sure that the tools that the staff have are up to date and periodically reinvested or rehabilitated so that they can be used to the highest degree of effectiveness.

96
00:08:18,525 --> 00:08:22,967
The other thing that a CIP really should help you avoid is costly emergency repairs.

97
00:08:23,528 --> 00:08:36,454
So if you have a school building and you know that the roof is 20 years old, you better start taking a look and inspecting it to make sure that you know when it needs to be replaced.

98
00:08:36,614 --> 00:08:45,498
If you don't, and there is a catastrophic leak, you would be forced to make an emergency repair, most likely at significant cost.

99
00:08:48,052 --> 00:08:53,016
Another potential pitfall of not having a CIP is poorly managed or poorly timed projects.

100
00:08:53,477 --> 00:09:00,463
And the classic example is you have a water main that needs to be replaced.

101
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:04,004
and you have a road that needs to be reconstructed.

102
00:09:04,344 --> 00:09:11,653
Well, you should do the water main first and then the road, because if you do the road and then you need to make a repair on the water main, you're going to have to dig up the road.

103
00:09:12,033 --> 00:09:22,505
And so the timing of projects can be quite complicated in a municipality, and so it's really important to have a plan that thinks through the phasing of certain projects.

104
00:09:24,431 --> 00:09:35,019
Another issue with not having a robust capital improvement plan is you may have inconsistent debt service, which is really difficult to accommodate in an operating budget.

105
00:09:35,060 --> 00:09:41,725
You don't want your debt service to be a million dollars one year and then 750 the next and then one and a half million.

106
00:09:41,985 --> 00:09:44,027
You really want smooth debt service.

107
00:09:44,087 --> 00:09:44,867
And that's the best

108
00:09:46,048 --> 00:09:48,670
approach from a financial perspective.

109
00:09:48,690 --> 00:09:55,334
And so planning helps you make sure that you can maintain that consistent debt service year over year.

110
00:09:57,196 --> 00:10:03,638
And then the last one on here is general financial disorder and negative impacts on bond ratings.

111
00:10:03,678 --> 00:10:18,121
So the rating agencies that determine a city or town's bond ratings do look to see whether the city or town has a capital improvement plan, along with a lot of other things like a financial forecast, financial policies, etc.

112
00:10:18,881 --> 00:10:23,786
And that's an indicator to the credit rating agencies that the city is well run.

113
00:10:23,886 --> 00:10:28,691
And so it's really important that the city maintain an up-to-date, robust capital improvement plan.

114
00:10:33,996 --> 00:10:37,279
So this is a typical capital improvement planning process.

115
00:10:39,158 --> 00:10:39,658
for the city.

116
00:10:40,379 --> 00:10:55,025
So sometime typically in late summer or early fall, the administration and finance teams would develop what we call a capital investment strategy, which is based on a financial forecast and projected resources.

117
00:10:55,725 --> 00:11:04,527
The capital investment strategy is really the financial plan in terms of how much money is available to be invested in capital.

118
00:11:04,587 --> 00:11:10,168
And I'm going to talk more specifically about what the capital investment strategy is, and I'd be happy to answer any questions.

119
00:11:11,408 --> 00:11:22,670
Part of what they'll look at when they're developing the investment strategy is the historical spending, the historical budget, and looking at projecting what the operating budget is going to be out in the future.

120
00:11:24,420 --> 00:11:37,230
And then in the fall, all the departments are going to be surveyed so that the city can understand capital needs, understand the priorities, and understand what grant opportunities are out there.

121
00:11:37,791 --> 00:11:41,053
So the department heads are a really integral part of the process.

122
00:11:41,774 --> 00:11:47,779
And I can't really stress enough how much work the department heads have done

123
00:11:49,380 --> 00:12:05,929
Over the last year on this capital improvement plan, they really are providing so much information, and I really want to commend them all because they were all wonderful to work with.

124
00:12:07,289 --> 00:12:17,715
In early winter, the project requests are reviewed and assessed for their adherence to citywide goals and priorities, and the capital investment strategy is finalized.

125
00:12:18,568 --> 00:12:20,580
So one note on priorities.

126
00:12:23,435 --> 00:12:32,062
It's the department heads who are providing really good information about what the top priorities are for their departments.

127
00:12:32,923 --> 00:12:46,634
And that is invaluable because in a city the size of Medford, it's nearly impossible for one person to fully understand all the priorities that are going on.

128
00:12:47,094 --> 00:12:52,399
So we really rely on the department heads and take into consideration what they're telling us the priorities are.

129
00:12:54,690 --> 00:12:58,753
So, and then also in early winter, the capital investment strategy is finalized.

130
00:12:58,793 --> 00:13:12,704
Sometimes there's more information that will inform the capital investment strategy, things like developments in the operating budget process or information coming out of the state in terms of their own budgeting process.

131
00:13:14,509 --> 00:13:29,879
Then in the spring the capital plan is finalized and presented to city council, and then on an ongoing basis, the administration and finance staff need to provide oversight, while the departments are initiating and managing the projects, you know that is a really important.

132
00:13:30,900 --> 00:13:34,942
piece of capital planning that doesn't get talked about a lot.

133
00:13:35,523 --> 00:13:38,204
Once you have the plan, it's time to execute on the plan.

134
00:13:38,744 --> 00:13:48,429
And so one of the considerations that I always need to think of and I need to communicate is, what are departments able to manage in terms of projects?

135
00:13:48,690 --> 00:13:54,473
There are some departments, planning departments, DPWs, engineering.

136
00:13:54,833 --> 00:13:58,515
There are a lot of projects that they see as needed.

137
00:13:59,275 --> 00:14:06,466
And sometimes you don't have the staff resources to manage all those projects, let alone the funding to actually pay for them.

138
00:14:06,807 --> 00:14:08,088
So that's an important consideration.

139
00:14:09,845 --> 00:14:16,910
I will say that the project plan, which is the list of projects, is really a dynamic document.

140
00:14:17,951 --> 00:14:21,093
Priorities can change, resources can change.

141
00:14:21,874 --> 00:14:30,420
And so it's really important that the capital planning process be considered an ongoing annual process, just like you would an operating budget.

142
00:14:34,743 --> 00:14:36,884
Sarah, we have a question from Vice President Behrs.

143
00:14:37,384 --> 00:14:37,945
OK, excellent.

144
00:14:39,917 --> 00:14:41,798
Hi Sarah, thanks for the presentation so far.

145
00:14:43,018 --> 00:14:49,780
I just have a question on the survey of capital needs and opportunities.

146
00:14:51,620 --> 00:15:05,124
Could you go a little bit more into how the process occurred, and were there like standard operating practices that the call and center recommended to the city to conduct that process and then also to conduct the annual review, and then I have a follow up after that.

147
00:15:06,143 --> 00:15:12,241
Yeah, so what we did this year is take the list of capital needs

148
00:15:14,095 --> 00:15:16,637
which I typically will call the capital needs assessment.

149
00:15:17,437 --> 00:15:21,419
And that is basically a big spreadsheet of all of the projects.

150
00:15:22,580 --> 00:15:26,162
And we send that back out to departments.

151
00:15:26,302 --> 00:15:29,644
And we say, what has stayed the same?

152
00:15:30,345 --> 00:15:31,305
What has changed?

153
00:15:31,606 --> 00:15:40,651
Whether it is the scope of a project that's changed, whether it is the cost of a project that's changed, maybe last year,

154
00:15:42,852 --> 00:15:55,018
engineering told us that they were going to reconstruct a road, but now they realize they can only afford a smaller section or they need more money to do the full section.

155
00:15:56,438 --> 00:16:02,661
Project scope can change, project costs can change, and priorities can change.

156
00:16:02,801 --> 00:16:06,563
Basically, what we did was send that information back out to department heads and said,

157
00:16:07,423 --> 00:16:19,562
please let us know what has changed and add any projects that you weren't aware of two years ago that you now feel are high enough priority that you want to add them to the list.

158
00:16:19,642 --> 00:16:21,345
So that's the way that it typically works.

159
00:16:23,339 --> 00:16:26,400
And I will say, you know, the process can be difficult to manage.

160
00:16:26,440 --> 00:16:35,823
It's a lot of information going back and forth and departments can be on different timelines in terms of when they get information, when grant opportunities open up for them.

161
00:16:36,223 --> 00:16:50,587
And so it certainly is, it's a lot of work to manage and, you know, sometimes can be a bit messy as all municipal work can be, but that was the typical process.

162
00:16:50,607 --> 00:16:52,628
And that's the process that we followed last year.

163
00:16:54,623 --> 00:16:54,963
Thank you.

164
00:16:54,983 --> 00:16:56,785
Yeah, I guess that that brings me to my question.

165
00:16:56,865 --> 00:17:04,471
So my next question, which is, it sounds like this was kind of a project based assessment.

166
00:17:04,911 --> 00:17:18,221
And I'm wondering if that would be different from an asset based assessment in the sense that it sounds like we have a list of projects that people think we need, but we maybe don't have a list of all of the city's capital assets and what their actual needs are.

167
00:17:19,302 --> 00:17:20,083
Is that correct?

168
00:17:20,163 --> 00:17:22,845
Or am I, you know, am I misunderstanding it a little bit?

169
00:17:24,245 --> 00:17:35,290
Well, for a department head, a department head should have a list of their capital assets.

170
00:17:36,250 --> 00:17:44,154
And they are the experts in their capital assets, and they are the ones who review their capital assets.

171
00:17:44,554 --> 00:17:49,116
And then based on the condition, the use, et cetera,

172
00:17:50,975 --> 00:17:54,881
define projects that they feel are needed.

173
00:17:56,203 --> 00:18:02,091
One thing I will say the Collins Center is not strongly supportive of is

174
00:18:04,593 --> 00:18:08,916
Taking a look at asset lists, let's say you have a list of dump trucks, right?

175
00:18:09,816 --> 00:18:19,682
There's no, there are guidance, there's best practices around, or I shouldn't say best practices, there are typical lifespans, right?

176
00:18:20,022 --> 00:18:26,666
And manufacturers will tell you that this asset has a lifespan of X years, five years, 20 years, whatever it is.

177
00:18:28,978 --> 00:18:30,879
And there are guidelines that do exist.

178
00:18:31,059 --> 00:18:36,864
So, for example, fire engines and fire ladder trucks have there's guidance from NFPA about

179
00:18:37,969 --> 00:18:44,173
how long those should be used on the front line, how long they should be used as backup or second string.

180
00:18:45,073 --> 00:18:55,320
But those types of guidelines are great starting points, but they would not really be appropriately used to say, OK, your dump truck is 25 years old.

181
00:18:55,360 --> 00:18:56,720
You have to replace it this year.

182
00:18:57,321 --> 00:19:01,723
There are some communities, because environmental impacts can be really significant.

183
00:19:02,304 --> 00:19:03,805
There are some communities that keep

184
00:19:04,345 --> 00:19:08,210
police cruisers for three years, and some communities that keep them for seven years.

185
00:19:08,631 --> 00:19:14,238
Dump trucks, likewise, may last 10 years in one environment, but 20 years in another environment.

186
00:19:14,258 --> 00:19:21,587
So we don't take, and I'm not sure whether that's what you're referring to when you say an asset-based approach, but the call-in center is not

187
00:19:22,969 --> 00:19:36,375
doesn't typically recommend taking a look at an asset inventory divorced from the unique context that the department heads would be able to provide about an asset's condition, performance, etc.

188
00:19:36,395 --> 00:19:37,915
Does that answer your question?

189
00:19:39,136 --> 00:19:41,457
Kind of, and I appreciate the context.

190
00:19:43,153 --> 00:19:47,175
more to me that this the CIP has always felt like step two in a process to me.

191
00:19:47,755 --> 00:19:51,237
And that's it sounds to me like step one is kind of just living in people's heads.

192
00:19:51,898 --> 00:19:55,159
And and that would be saying here are all of our capital assets.

193
00:19:55,860 --> 00:19:57,080
And this is what they're worth.

194
00:19:57,120 --> 00:19:58,301
This is how old they are.

195
00:19:58,961 --> 00:20:10,791
These are, you know, the issues we have with them and I don't necessarily mean, you know, more replaceable assets like a vehicle more I'm thinking about fixed assets like a building or roads and sidewalks.

196
00:20:11,552 --> 00:20:27,705
And, and the reason I'm asking is just like I think it's great to have a capital improvement plan and to say here are the projects that department heads think are the top priority for us to do, but I think the issue that we always have on the council and I think the public has is understanding, how did we get from what is our current condition.

197
00:20:28,265 --> 00:20:47,507
to prioritizing specific projects and, and, you know, so that that's why this is always felt like a step two to me, and something that we've been working on as a council is looking at a creating an ordinance for our budget to assess both our operating needs and our capital needs, so that we can have a shared framework and understanding of exactly

198
00:20:48,047 --> 00:21:13,494
the facts behind all of that so I don't know if I'm explaining myself entirely correctly but I guess what I'm saying is, you know, step one to me and all of this would be saying, hey every department head, what are all of our capital assets that you manage, put that in one place, then we have a list of all of our assets, then we know, you know, we can say okay Medford High School that's a capital asset we have, you know, what do we think the need is for you know

199
00:21:14,718 --> 00:21:18,480
bringing that up, you know, addressing all deferred maintenance on that asset.

