00:22:48,649 --> 00:22:56,532
That is sort of, it was written for the public so that they could understand how extensive and expansive the capital asset

216
00:22:57,512 --> 00:23:01,194
inventory is in the city, you know, the municipally owned capital asset inventory.

217
00:23:01,715 --> 00:23:21,786
So there are lists of all of the parks with some basic information, you know, I think acreage and use, lists of the buildings, how many road miles, how many are residential, how many are collector roads, how many bridges, what are the years of the bridges, when were they built, when were they rehabbed, are they, you know, obviously municipally owned,

218
00:23:22,466 --> 00:23:23,747
And things like that.

219
00:23:23,827 --> 00:23:25,628
So those things do exist.

220
00:23:26,448 --> 00:23:27,108
Absolutely.

221
00:23:27,128 --> 00:23:29,269
Great.

222
00:23:29,289 --> 00:23:31,130
Well, sorry, go ahead.

223
00:23:31,410 --> 00:23:39,193
Well, I was going to say, and they are also the basis of generating the projects in the capital plan.

224
00:23:41,254 --> 00:23:41,534
Great.

225
00:23:41,614 --> 00:23:42,335
Well, that's helpful.

226
00:23:44,371 --> 00:23:45,512
to have that information.

227
00:23:45,832 --> 00:23:52,854
Did that document include on the asset inventory list, like the cost it would take for each asset to bring it to a state of good repair?

228
00:23:56,876 --> 00:23:57,336
No.

229
00:23:59,897 --> 00:24:05,739
That's a difficult question to answer, Councilman, because there

230
00:24:11,828 --> 00:24:12,749
It's a great question.

231
00:24:13,409 --> 00:24:19,912
And certainly, if there was somebody who was the capital projects manager, that may be something that they could pursue.

232
00:24:19,932 --> 00:24:34,577
But it is quite a bit of work and probably something that would not be accomplishable with city human resources, simply because it would be a staggering amount of work to do it that way.

233
00:24:35,678 --> 00:24:38,299
What I will say is that the departments

234
00:24:39,079 --> 00:24:44,541
staff are the ones who are using the assets all of the time.

235
00:24:45,021 --> 00:24:54,444
And so they are working to prioritize, defining the projects that they know are most needed.

236
00:24:55,384 --> 00:25:02,787
Certainly there are projects that could be needed, maybe are lower priority, that potentially didn't make it to our list.

237
00:25:02,887 --> 00:25:04,468
Although I will say, I think we've got

238
00:25:07,440 --> 00:25:10,401
I can you I don't want to misstate the number but you'll see it in a few minutes.

239
00:25:10,481 --> 00:25:14,402
There are more than 100 projects on the capital plan.

240
00:25:15,482 --> 00:25:18,743
And so, certainly, it's quite extensive.

241
00:25:21,183 --> 00:25:27,365
Yeah, that's helpful and I appreciate I understand it's a difficult process but I think you know for us from

242
00:25:27,963 --> 00:25:38,831
a city financial planning perspective, there really is a need for us to have that figure you know one of the most helpful documents that we have right now is the road and sidewalk condition and

243
00:25:39,690 --> 00:25:51,158
reports and the assessments that came along with that, where we now have an actual dollar number you know over nine figures about how much the city needs to spend to bring our roads and sidewalks into a state of good repair.

244
00:25:51,618 --> 00:25:58,783
And I think for financial planning purposes, you know, having something like that for all of our assets really needs to be a goal and I know it's not your job to

245
00:25:59,603 --> 00:26:00,143
to do that.

246
00:26:00,183 --> 00:26:03,444
So I'm not asking you to obviously speak towards that.

247
00:26:03,504 --> 00:26:08,645
But it sounds like we have a lot of really great data from the last process that you did and from this process.

248
00:26:09,245 --> 00:26:20,848
And that, you know, pulling all that together and working potentially with an outside consultant to really nail down the dollar figures for what the needs are for capital needs.

249
00:26:20,888 --> 00:26:23,149
The dollar amount needs for capital needs is important.

250
00:26:23,509 --> 00:26:29,210
And completely hear you on department heads, you know, knowing their assets the best and suggesting what the best

251
00:26:30,170 --> 00:26:46,997
most urgent needs are for capital funding but you know I think exactly what you just said about you know there may be other lower priority needs that don't get included, that's what we need to know about to you know the capital improvement is to me, how much we're investing and trying to bring us back to a state of good repair.

252
00:26:47,497 --> 00:26:52,318
but the figure that we don't have is what actually would everything in a state of good repair be.

253
00:26:52,719 --> 00:26:55,980
And that's what we need to be able to benchmark progress in my opinion.

254
00:26:56,060 --> 00:27:09,924
So just putting that out there, I completely understand your role in the process and that most of what I said is not your role, but I really appreciate your expertise and giving me the details I need to better understand what we need to get to the place that I'm talking about.

255
00:27:09,964 --> 00:27:10,684
So thank you very much.

256
00:27:11,384 --> 00:27:23,227
I will say that the pavement condition index is an absolutely vital tool that was also grant funded and was a great process for the city to go through.

257
00:27:23,247 --> 00:27:26,868
So that's great.

258
00:27:28,169 --> 00:27:33,170
It would be amazing if you had that type of report for each asset type.

259
00:27:34,531 --> 00:27:48,892
The other type of assessment that municipalities often do is to hire an architectural firm that can come in and do really deep facilities assessments, you know, the facade,

260
00:27:49,553 --> 00:27:57,319
all of the HVAC, the plumbing, all of that, and they can generate that number that you'd be looking for for facilities.

261
00:27:57,660 --> 00:28:14,774
Of course, that's quite a costly endeavor to bring in a consultant to do that, but I absolutely agree it's an invaluable tool not only for city council, but also for the department heads to help them understand what is the true cost and is there anything that I'm just not seeing.

262
00:28:14,794 --> 00:28:16,475
I really appreciate your comments.

263
00:28:18,500 --> 00:28:19,000
Thank you.

264
00:28:19,060 --> 00:28:19,881
Yeah, and could you.

265
00:28:20,021 --> 00:28:45,833
I'm sorry to Bogart I know I'm my other fellow counselor the question but just how often that that the index, the either the process that you did at the beginning where you surveyed all the department has to get capital needs or the thing that we did for roads and sidewalk conditions how often would you suggest we do that iteratively, should it be every five year capital improvement plan we also do that, or should it be more more regular or less regular.

266
00:28:47,902 --> 00:28:55,387
I think that just feasibly, every five years is a great target.

267
00:28:55,447 --> 00:29:11,998
I mean, the thing about the pavement condition index, and certainly your DPW and engineering staff can talk more specifically about it, is if you, and just like any plan, say you do a road assessment, and then you say, oh, that's great, look at all that money we need to spend, and then you don't,

268
00:29:12,698 --> 00:29:18,681
follow up with the actual investment or try to get close to it, then the PCI becomes very stale.

269
00:29:19,021 --> 00:29:37,110
But if you're updating it and your staff know how to say, yes, we did do that road, let's put in the new PCI for that road, and it shows you and it's sort of constantly updated, then you have a better chance of stretching out how often you need to do that sort of consulting project.

270
00:29:37,510 --> 00:29:38,131
Does that make sense?

271
00:29:38,971 --> 00:29:39,612
Thank you so much.

272
00:29:39,672 --> 00:29:40,172
Yes, thank you.

273
00:29:40,597 --> 00:29:40,817
Thank you.

274
00:29:40,837 --> 00:29:43,960
We have a question from Councilor saying and then we'll go to Councilor Carvio after that.

275
00:29:44,961 --> 00:29:45,361
Thank you.

276
00:29:45,701 --> 00:29:54,729
Um, so, I think, Councilor bears made some great points about needing to look at our assets and as a whole.

277
00:29:55,530 --> 00:30:03,437
Um, I think something that runs through my mind, as well as that there might be important projects that are important to residents in the city but, um,

278
00:30:04,818 --> 00:30:07,439
They might not have the resources to reach out to city government.

279
00:30:07,479 --> 00:30:09,020
They might not know who to go to.

280
00:30:09,100 --> 00:30:17,304
And so there might be a disconnect in a way between what we hear at City Hall versus what residents on the ground want.

281
00:30:18,324 --> 00:30:22,866
And of course, I do trust our department heads to know best what types of projects we need.

282
00:30:23,266 --> 00:30:33,651
But I was wondering if what you saw is the role of community feedback and resident engagement in this process.

283
00:30:34,066 --> 00:30:36,968
Yeah, thank you so much for asking that, Councilor Seng.

284
00:30:37,008 --> 00:30:40,050
It's such an important component of capital planning.

285
00:30:40,551 --> 00:30:58,103
So there are a couple of different ways that residents can contribute to the capital planning process, because the capital plan is actually built on all sorts of other plans that already exist or should exist.

286
00:30:58,543 --> 00:31:00,265
So just I'll give you one example.

287
00:31:01,400 --> 00:31:07,428
The municipalities in Massachusetts are all required if they want to get certain grants to have an open space and recreation plan.

288
00:31:08,469 --> 00:31:15,838
And that plan, a master plan, and various other types of plans are really

289
00:31:17,192 --> 00:31:22,895
processes that are deeply, deeply, or should be deeply engaging with the community.

290
00:31:23,515 --> 00:31:33,180
And municipalities have really, I think, in the last number of years, kind of expanded their view of what engagement means.

291
00:31:33,240 --> 00:31:38,883
It doesn't just mean saying there's going to be a meeting, posting an agenda, and saying, hey, we have a public meeting.

292
00:31:38,923 --> 00:31:39,944
Come if you find out.

293
00:31:40,084 --> 00:31:41,985
Come if you come to the website and find out about it.

294
00:31:42,585 --> 00:31:45,067
It's really more proactive than that.

295
00:31:45,468 --> 00:31:53,455
And so cities and towns in Massachusetts have been doing a decent job of trying to really build out their capital engagement capacity.

296
00:31:53,756 --> 00:31:58,680
And that means going, say you have a charrette, you know, or say you have a

297
00:31:59,581 --> 00:32:10,807
A charrette's like a meeting, for those who don't know, a charrette's like a meeting where people can come and really deeply engage with planning and land use type of activities.

298
00:32:11,328 --> 00:32:20,133
And so it might mean something like going to, leaving City Hall and bringing that charrette activity to a community center.

299
00:32:20,853 --> 00:32:22,874
or a school where people are comfortable.

300
00:32:23,134 --> 00:32:27,697
They may not be comfortable going to City Hall, but they may be comfortable going to their child's school to participate.

301
00:32:28,217 --> 00:32:33,260
It also means offering meetings in different languages to meet people where they are.

302
00:32:33,440 --> 00:32:41,404
It may mean something as small as providing child care so that people with young families where kids can't be left alone can participate.

303
00:32:41,464 --> 00:32:43,225
And so it's such an important part

304
00:32:43,925 --> 00:32:47,789
So the capital planning process is built on those types of plans.

305
00:32:48,169 --> 00:33:02,563
So when you're planning development and sustainability department provides me with the list of park projects that they see as priorities, what they're doing is referencing the plans that have been built with strong community engagement.

306
00:33:03,023 --> 00:33:03,723
So that's one thing.

307
00:33:04,664 --> 00:33:15,769
But the other thing, which is really interesting, is that I've seen in some municipalities a more robust direct community engagement with the capital planning process.

308
00:33:16,209 --> 00:33:23,953
And it could be something like, now we didn't do this, but it's something that you could consider in the future, something along the lines of

309
00:33:25,313 --> 00:33:33,736
creating a form, a Google form or a digital form, where residents can contribute ideas for capital improvements.

310
00:33:34,516 --> 00:33:42,518
And they're not going to be able to tell you how much the road is going to cost, how much asphalt you need, but they're going to be able to tell you, hey, if this road's not on your list, it should be.

311
00:33:43,178 --> 00:33:48,600
Or they may tell you, I'm really disappointed that the school playgrounds are not accessible.

312
00:33:48,760 --> 00:33:54,244
And that might trigger the departments to say, oh, yes, I'm seeing a lot of conversation.

313
00:33:54,304 --> 00:33:58,006
I'm hearing a lot from community members that this is important.

314
00:33:58,687 --> 00:34:00,188
And that could elevate a project.

315
00:34:01,448 --> 00:34:03,470
And there may be other ways to engage

316
00:34:03,950 --> 00:34:05,091
community members.

317
00:34:05,151 --> 00:34:15,458
So you could look for individuals, but you could also go to community-based organizations that maybe speak for a larger demographic group and say, hey, what are you seeing?

318
00:34:15,859 --> 00:34:24,065
Any capital needs that you see could be PTAs, it could be religious groups, it could be, you know, different affinity groups.

319
00:34:24,905 --> 00:34:30,247
So that's a really interesting and innovative way of engaging the public in the capital planning process.

320
00:34:30,627 --> 00:34:38,190
Again, not something that's very widespread, but something that's on the cutting edge, something that I'd absolutely recommend that you all consider.

321
00:34:39,691 --> 00:34:49,535
And if you have more questions about that, I'd be happy to think about who I know in other cities and towns that have done things similar, and maybe we can make a connection.

322
00:34:51,298 --> 00:34:52,019
Thank you so much.

323
00:34:52,159 --> 00:34:58,704
I think you read my mind on the next question, which is that, you know, we do have a lot of plans, and I was wondering how this plan engaged with those plans.

324
00:34:59,445 --> 00:35:11,255
I have tons of questions, but I know you have more to present, so I'll let you get to that, but I did have a question because we started to talk a little bit about prioritization.

325
00:35:12,136 --> 00:35:23,652
And so I was wondering if there were metrics that we were using to evaluate how we prioritize projects or if it was really, you know, left up to department heads or to these plans.

326
00:35:24,397 --> 00:35:36,507
Yeah, so the Collins Center does have what we call a scoring methodology, which has a number of parameters with which we score projects.

327
00:35:36,588 --> 00:35:40,891
And there are things that you would expect, things like, is there a public safety issue?

328
00:35:42,152 --> 00:35:45,095
Does this project advance environmental concerns?

329
00:35:45,215 --> 00:35:47,697
Does it have an economic development benefit to the town?

330
00:35:47,877 --> 00:35:49,679
Is there external funding available?

331
00:35:49,699 --> 00:35:50,279
Things like that.

332
00:35:52,280 --> 00:36:04,324
In this particular case, the process we went through in the past year, what we did was we were able to essentially accommodate all, basically all of the projects that the department heads identified.

333
00:36:04,864 --> 00:36:07,704
We just spread it actually over seven years.

334
00:36:07,724 --> 00:36:17,307
So there were a handful of projects that got pushed out to FY29, but we were able to accommodate basically all of the projects that departments

335
00:36:17,687 --> 00:36:19,047
identified as priorities.

336
00:36:20,188 --> 00:36:21,648
And so that was really great.

337
00:36:21,688 --> 00:36:24,368
But we do have that scoring methodology that goes through.

338
00:36:24,389 --> 00:36:27,869
I can't remember if it's 15 parameters or 19, something like that.

339
00:36:28,769 --> 00:36:32,910
And those are really, and department prioritization is one of the very important ones.

340
00:36:34,931 --> 00:36:38,512
But those are, that scoring is very useful for

341
00:36:40,392 --> 00:36:44,074
for guiding a conversation, especially if financial resources are tight.

342
00:36:44,514 --> 00:36:55,741
Now, I will say in this particular case, we've had a special, you know, very unique funding source, ARPA, which has really changed the game in terms of

343
00:36:56,561 --> 00:37:01,584
you know, these couple of years where we can spend it on capital needs.

344
00:37:01,844 --> 00:37:03,765
So that's a little bit of an anomaly.

345
00:37:04,685 --> 00:37:12,730
And so the scoring becomes less imperative, because there are a lot of resources out there.

346
00:37:13,530 --> 00:37:20,637
But yes, absolutely, you need to have some sort of methodology that allows you to assess objectively the different projects.

347
00:37:20,757 --> 00:37:24,320
And if there are financial constraints, you have to make difficult decisions.

348
00:37:24,360 --> 00:37:30,725
And sometimes it can be really challenging to say, well, what's more important, you know, a dump truck or three new cruisers?

349
00:37:30,765 --> 00:37:33,848
Like they're both super important, both absolutely essential.

350
00:37:33,908 --> 00:37:37,851
So how do we make that work within a financially feasible plan?

351
00:37:38,192 --> 00:37:39,473
It can be a challenge.

352
00:37:44,453 --> 00:37:45,634
We'll go to Councilor Carviel.

353
00:37:46,395 --> 00:37:47,416
Thank you, Madam President.

354
00:37:47,957 --> 00:37:49,559
Thank you sir for the presentation so far.

355
00:37:50,480 --> 00:37:56,267
I agree with Councilor Baez and what he said it earlier that I think maybe we are putting the cart in front of the horse here a little bit.

356
00:37:58,289 --> 00:38:02,294
Being on this council longer than anybody else, I've seen capital plans come and go in this community.

357
00:38:03,700 --> 00:38:08,783
We see them, we develop them, and they never really ever come to fruition.

358
00:38:09,103 --> 00:38:11,245
Maybe one or two things ever happen on them.

359
00:38:11,265 --> 00:38:21,911
But I think the city is at the point where right now is, I think we need to take stock of our assets and see where they are and the condition that they're in.

360
00:38:24,132 --> 00:38:27,915
We have a history in this community of letting our assets

361
00:38:28,695 --> 00:38:29,816
just really fall apart.

362
00:38:30,457 --> 00:38:42,431
So over the last six years, or maybe a little longer, we have a brand new DPW building, we have a new police station, and we have a new library.

363
00:38:42,572 --> 00:38:48,218
And before then, the only really capital improvements that we ever did was we built

364
00:38:49,019 --> 00:38:59,388
the new schools, and now those, those schools are 20 plus years old, and we didn't do our job as as as a city and maintain them.

365
00:39:00,629 --> 00:39:06,494
So I say, so I think you'll tell me his idea of, let's, let's get our assets

366
00:39:07,518 --> 00:39:13,963
down on paper, see what condition they are, and then we can develop our priorities and know where we have to go.

367
00:39:14,364 --> 00:39:18,828
And my other question is, do we have the staff

368
00:39:20,037 --> 00:39:23,140
to see the capital improvement plans coming through.

369
00:39:24,001 --> 00:39:27,084
Every department we have right now is short staffed here.

370
00:39:27,905 --> 00:39:31,909
Some departments don't even have department heads.

371
00:39:32,329 --> 00:39:36,853
So that's a concern that I share with the capital plan going forward.

372
00:39:37,334 --> 00:39:41,478
So just my opinion for the next few minutes and then I'll come back with some more questions after.

373
00:39:42,582 --> 00:39:43,503
Yeah, excellent.

374
00:39:43,543 --> 00:39:45,264
Thank you for those comments, Councilman.

375
00:39:46,305 --> 00:39:47,686
I think you're absolutely right.

376
00:39:47,886 --> 00:39:54,611
Just to go to your last point first, you need to have the staff to manage projects.

377
00:39:54,751 --> 00:40:05,639
Now, some projects can be done in-house to a large degree, but most of them need to be, you need to procure experts to do them.

378
00:40:06,220 --> 00:40:08,841
And then you need to provide oversight for those

379
00:40:09,842 --> 00:40:11,043
those contractors.

380
00:40:11,163 --> 00:40:15,026
And so you do need human resources to manage a capital plan.

381
00:40:15,406 --> 00:40:16,006
Absolutely.

382
00:40:16,066 --> 00:40:22,410
And that is a challenge for Medford and many cities and towns around the Commonwealth.

383
00:40:23,431 --> 00:40:31,376
And the other issue with human resources is directly tied to your point about deferred maintenance.

384
00:40:33,137 --> 00:40:46,937
Many communities can spend a decade moving toward a major construction of a new building, and it's a lot of work, and getting everybody to buy in, figuring out how we're going to fund it, maybe pursuing a debt exclusion.

385
00:40:48,078 --> 00:41:03,205
But then if you don't have the staff to do the regular preventive maintenance on the building, checking those HVAC filters, cleaning things, and just monitoring what's going on with the systems, then they're not going to last as long as they should.

386
00:41:03,606 --> 00:41:07,888
And so that's a really significant challenge for cities and towns around the Commonwealth.

387
00:41:07,968 --> 00:41:10,529
Those costs fall within the operating budget.

388
00:41:11,430 --> 00:41:20,178
And, you know, obviously you guys know very well how challenging developing the operating budget and funding what really needs to be funded can be.

389
00:41:20,198 --> 00:41:24,022
Thank you.

390
00:41:24,082 --> 00:41:26,965
I believe that's the questions we have for now, if you want to proceed.

391
00:41:27,385 --> 00:41:28,006
Okay, thank you.

392
00:41:28,847 --> 00:41:29,107
Thank you.

393
00:41:33,492 --> 00:41:42,595
Um, actually this is a this is a good slide to come up next, you know, to the to the to the counselors points about what are the capital assets in Bedford.

394
00:41:43,035 --> 00:41:51,578
This is a summary that comes from the chapter that I had mentioned to a few minutes ago.

395
00:41:51,998 --> 00:41:52,118
So,

396
00:41:53,118 --> 00:41:56,401
In Medford, there are a lot of capital assets that are municipally owned.

397
00:41:57,162 --> 00:42:03,147
There are more than a dozen city-owned buildings, police, fire stations, library, city hall, DPW yard.

398
00:42:03,888 --> 00:42:08,772
There are nine school facilities and associated components like athletic fields and parking lots.

399
00:42:09,953 --> 00:42:13,756
You have IT assets, computers, tablets, network components.

400
00:42:14,557 --> 00:42:22,606
And then there are many, many vehicles, trailers, mowers, sedans, police cruisers, dump trucks, fire engines, ladder trucks.

401
00:42:22,666 --> 00:42:28,933
I mean, these run the gamut from a $15,000 trailer to a million dollar ladder truck.

402
00:42:29,033 --> 00:42:32,096
So many, many vehicles across multiple departments.

403
00:42:32,917 --> 00:42:40,641
You have dozens of parks and recreation sites, including playgrounds, trails, athletic courts, athletic fields, pool, pond, skating rink.

404
00:42:41,261 --> 00:42:47,984
You have a lot of recreational assets in the city, and a lot of them need capital improvement.

405
00:42:48,885 --> 00:42:52,506
You also have passive use open space like veteran squares and monuments.

406
00:42:54,437 --> 00:42:55,638
cemeteries, things like that.

407
00:42:56,298 --> 00:43:05,084
You have 92 miles of roads and many, many, many, many miles of sidewalks that need to be maintained and improved from time to time.

408
00:43:05,824 --> 00:43:07,546
There are two city-owned bridges.

409
00:43:08,946 --> 00:43:13,089
There are countless culverts, drainage pipes, and there's even a dam.

410
00:43:13,689 --> 00:43:16,531
And then you have your water distribution and sewer collection systems.

411
00:43:17,092 --> 00:43:21,434
So there are a lot of assets.

412
00:43:21,475 --> 00:43:23,656
The counselor mentioned the pavement

413
00:43:26,098 --> 00:43:28,361
road assessment, that's one very common one.

414
00:43:28,821 --> 00:43:43,557
As I mentioned, facilities are also typically, well maybe I shouldn't say typically, it's not uncommon for cities and towns to bring in architectural firms to assess, do a facilities assessment on their facilities.

415
00:43:44,318 --> 00:43:50,102
Water and sewer systems often will have assessments done by professional engineering firms.

416
00:43:50,522 --> 00:44:00,848
So those are the kind of first places I would guide you toward if you are serious about finding some money to bring in specialized consultants to take a look at your assets.

417
00:44:01,228 --> 00:44:03,390
Those are the ones that are most commonly targeted.

418
00:44:03,410 --> 00:44:13,216
I want to shift and talk about the

419
00:44:14,380 --> 00:44:15,462
investment strategy.

420
00:44:15,482 --> 00:44:19,648
And GF is a short way of saying general fund.

421
00:44:20,269 --> 00:44:24,395
So this is general fund only, it doesn't include the enterprise funds, water and sewer.

422
00:44:26,200 --> 00:44:30,942
So the capital investment strategy is based on historical data.

423
00:44:31,262 --> 00:44:37,885
Trend analysis is obviously a foundation of a lot of financial projections and planning.

424
00:44:38,685 --> 00:44:51,631
So here we look at three years of historical capital investment, and we compare that to the net budget, which is reported to the state on the recap sheet.

425
00:44:53,014 --> 00:44:54,315
So I'm going to walk you through this table.

426
00:44:55,015 --> 00:44:58,657
The top boxes are the existing capital investment.

427
00:44:58,917 --> 00:45:03,099
So the first line is your existing net general fund non-excluded debt.

428
00:45:03,839 --> 00:45:10,362
And when I say net, that means that if you have any subsidies, like from revolving funds, things like that, that's all netted out.

429
00:45:10,702 --> 00:45:15,384
So in 21, 22, 23, those were your debt service figures for the general fund.

430
00:45:17,607 --> 00:45:19,749
Then you have a capital lease for a fire truck.

431
00:45:20,389 --> 00:45:27,054
And in 2022 and 2023, half of that capital lease was funded from the general fund operating budget.

432
00:45:28,655 --> 00:45:33,618
And then you also have what is typically called pay-go spending or pay-as-you-go spending.

433
00:45:33,999 --> 00:45:36,661
That's cash that's spent on capital projects.

434
00:45:37,301 --> 00:45:39,683
Most likely and most typically, it's free cash.

435
00:45:42,413 --> 00:45:44,974
So I've added that as a note, free cash.

436
00:45:45,634 --> 00:45:50,196
So 2021, 2022, there was no free cash spending, which I think is an anomaly.

437
00:45:50,796 --> 00:45:58,198
In 2023, so far, there's been slightly over 2.9 million appropriated from free cash for capital projects.

438
00:45:59,118 --> 00:46:10,462
So the line there that says total existing capital investment, that's the total of all the money you've spent from the general fund on capital projects for those three historical years.

439
00:46:11,969 --> 00:46:19,356
And then moving down to the second box, the first line there says net budget with a 4% projected annual growth figure.

440
00:46:20,677 --> 00:46:24,100
We calculate net budget using the recap sheet from the state.

441
00:46:25,181 --> 00:46:33,209
And we're using 4% as the projected annual growth moving, you know, as we move into the future, 24, 25, et cetera.

442
00:46:33,589 --> 00:46:37,673
But what you see in these boxes is the actual net budget.

443
00:46:39,515 --> 00:46:43,058
The next line says funded via debt as a percent of net budget.

444
00:46:43,178 --> 00:46:46,682
So that means what is your debt service as a percent of your net budget?

445
00:46:47,362 --> 00:46:51,766
And as you can see, it's somewhere, it's between three and 3.15%.

446
00:46:51,867 --> 00:46:56,851
That's a typical number.

447
00:46:57,111 --> 00:46:58,753
It is a strong number.

448
00:46:59,794 --> 00:47:01,255
It's not too low, it's not too high.

449
00:47:01,275 --> 00:47:04,218
I think it's a good number for the city.

450
00:47:23,973 --> 00:47:24,574
for FY23.

451
00:47:25,774 --> 00:47:29,295
And then the total capital spending as a percentage of net budget.

452
00:47:29,416 --> 00:47:30,596
So you can see those totaled up.

453
00:47:32,177 --> 00:47:37,799
So the bullet at the bottom just has some notes about kind of what we interpreted from the findings.

454
00:47:38,059 --> 00:47:45,362
So historically, the city has invested approximately three and a half percent of net budget in capital projects, both from debt and cash.

455
00:47:47,607 --> 00:47:55,511
ARPA funds have significantly impacted the CIP that was developed two years ago and significantly changed things.

456
00:47:57,412 --> 00:48:09,036
Because ARPA is cash, we can fund projects that previously may have been funded with debt, but now we have the opportunity to fund them with cash, saving the taxpayers dollars because they're not having to pay interest on those projects.

457
00:48:10,557 --> 00:48:12,518
And it really is a significant opportunity.

458
00:48:15,382 --> 00:48:18,305
Before I go to the next slide, I just want to make sure there are no questions about this.

459
00:48:18,325 --> 00:48:19,666
Did I explain it well enough?

460
00:48:22,148 --> 00:48:22,648
I believe so.

461
00:48:22,668 --> 00:48:23,709
I do not see any questions.

462
00:48:24,410 --> 00:48:24,730
Thank you.

463
00:48:27,392 --> 00:48:27,753
All right.

464
00:48:27,833 --> 00:48:38,322
So taking the historical data, conversing with the finance team about what they're seeing in terms of operating budget projections, their financial forecasting, et cetera.

465
00:48:39,537 --> 00:48:46,465
We developed a three pronged approach to the general fund capital investment strategy for the ensuing six years, five years.

466
00:48:47,583 --> 00:48:48,683
So one, free cash.

467
00:48:49,224 --> 00:48:57,146
We want to project free cash for capital investment conservatively because we really need to protect reserve levels.

468
00:48:57,266 --> 00:49:02,227
It's sort of been an economic whiplash from the start of the pandemic to today.

469
00:49:02,287 --> 00:49:03,608
There were dire projections.

470
00:49:03,688 --> 00:49:05,328
Then it turned out things weren't so bad.

471
00:49:05,688 --> 00:49:07,229
Now we have all this ARPA money.

472
00:49:07,709 --> 00:49:10,210
But what does the future hold in terms of the economy?

473
00:49:10,910 --> 00:49:18,201
We really don't know, but we do know that it's best practice, and it makes sense, and particularly in this case, to project conservatively.

474
00:49:18,361 --> 00:49:24,411
So we don't want to spend too much of our free cash because we want to keep some of it back to be held in reserve just in case we need it.

475
00:49:25,765 --> 00:49:29,648
The second prong of the strategy is those ARPA dollars.

476
00:49:30,528 --> 00:49:34,911
ARPA is really a unique opportunity to accelerate capital investment in the city.

477
00:49:35,431 --> 00:49:40,054
And there are some rules around when it needs to be committed and when it needs to be expended.

478
00:49:40,174 --> 00:49:51,042
And so you'll see that there's quite a lot of projects that are accomplished or have already been sort of committed.

479
00:49:51,182 --> 00:49:52,923
We've already committed a lot of our ARPA dollars.

480
00:49:53,243 --> 00:49:59,952
But then there's more that will be committed through this plan for capital spending.

481
00:50:00,593 --> 00:50:02,296
That is not something that's going to last forever.

482
00:50:02,396 --> 00:50:03,477
Obviously, there are time limits.

483
00:50:03,558 --> 00:50:07,042
But for the next several years, it's a key part of the plan.

484
00:50:08,172 --> 00:50:10,533
And then the third is the general fund debt.

485
00:50:11,093 --> 00:50:24,160
So our target says that we're going to try to keep general fund debt service at 3% of net budget to maintain affordability for residents and also to avoid significant up and down swings in the annual debt service payments.

486
00:50:24,500 --> 00:50:29,002
And that really is essential for operating budget development.

487
00:50:30,824 --> 00:50:35,786
In addition, the plan calls for water and sewer projects to be fully funded from enterprise fund revenues.

488
00:50:36,166 --> 00:50:44,190
So the enterprise fund is set up to run those services just like a business would, and it needs to cover all of its costs.

489
00:50:44,630 --> 00:50:48,972
And so there are two sources that the enterprise fund can use to pay for its capital projects.

490
00:50:49,032 --> 00:50:52,654
They have retained earnings, which is equivalent to free cash.

491
00:50:53,254 --> 00:51:00,337
And so any cash funded projects would be typically funded with retained earnings, and then they can also issue debt.

492
00:51:01,902 --> 00:51:14,758
And then the last piece of the plan, which is something that the city does really well is to continue to be aggressive and seeking grants, including MSBA and any other non tax levy funding sources.

493
00:51:15,398 --> 00:51:18,702
Obviously, this is something that just makes a ton of sense.

494
00:51:19,303 --> 00:51:21,664
for taxpayers.

495
00:51:22,405 --> 00:51:33,551
And there are a lot of opportunities at the state level that the city has a strong history of being very competitive for grants.

496
00:51:34,291 --> 00:51:45,357
And we're sort of entering a new era of opportunity from the federal government with the bipartisan infrastructure law, just kind of opening up the doors for a lot of infrastructure investment.

497
00:51:45,637 --> 00:51:51,099
And I actually think the city of Medford is really well positioned to take advantage of those opportunities.

498
00:51:56,021 --> 00:51:57,602
All right, so here's another table.

499
00:51:57,622 --> 00:52:04,084
And I'm going to walk you through it because I want to make sure that folks can understand and don't get confused.

500
00:52:04,705 --> 00:52:07,786
I'm going to move you guys so I can see this fully.

501
00:52:10,508 --> 00:52:15,555
The top is the same as the last table.

502
00:52:15,675 --> 00:52:21,062
That's existing capital investment, but it goes out to future years.

503
00:52:21,302 --> 00:52:22,223
So it includes 24, 25, 26, 27, 28.

504
00:52:25,071 --> 00:52:32,475
So we know, because the debt that you're issuing is long-term debt, we can project what those costs are going to be.

505
00:52:33,055 --> 00:52:37,577
And we can see that the debt changes over time.

506
00:52:38,818 --> 00:52:41,419
And we can also project capital leases.

507
00:52:42,539 --> 00:52:47,822
Here we have the lease for the fire truck listed in FY23.

508
00:52:48,843 --> 00:52:50,243
There are several more years of that.

509
00:52:50,323 --> 00:52:52,764
And those lease payments are actually included.

510
00:52:54,085 --> 00:52:56,307
in the plan to be funded from free cash.

511
00:52:57,567 --> 00:53:00,609
So those don't appear up at the top, but do appear in the bottom.

512
00:53:01,650 --> 00:53:09,235
And then obviously we don't know, there's no commitment yet in terms of PAYGO spending for those future years.

513
00:53:09,335 --> 00:53:13,358
That will come once we move forward with the plan that has been developed.

514
00:53:14,139 --> 00:53:18,261
So we know what the existing capital investment is where the city has to pay it.

515
00:53:18,361 --> 00:53:20,523
We have to pay for the debt that we've already issued.

516
00:53:22,280 --> 00:53:24,302
Then we can look at the net budget projection.

517
00:53:24,442 --> 00:53:31,427
So again, the net budget is based on a 4% projection.

518
00:53:32,127 --> 00:53:33,769
And we carry that annually.

519
00:53:34,269 --> 00:53:35,450
Now, that could change.

520
00:53:35,510 --> 00:53:44,336
It could be that after the FY23 budget is all settled and you start to get into the FY24 budget, the 4% feels wrong.

521
00:53:44,477 --> 00:53:45,197
Maybe it's too high.

522
00:53:45,217 --> 00:53:45,878
Maybe it's too low.

523
00:53:46,238 --> 00:53:47,499
That number can be changed.

524
00:53:48,019 --> 00:53:50,621
And obviously, it would impact the full plan.

525
00:53:50,641 --> 00:53:51,642
It would flow throughout the plan.

526
00:53:55,213 --> 00:54:01,881
So I'm in the middle of the, I'm in the, I'm in the third table here, the line where it says funded via debt as a percent of net budget.

527
00:54:02,282 --> 00:54:06,367
So that refers to the existing debt only, no new debt.

528
00:54:06,747 --> 00:54:09,831
So you can see the existing debt drops from three,

529
00:54:11,113 --> 00:54:14,815
percent to 2.7, 2.5, and so on down the line.

530
00:54:15,215 --> 00:54:30,122
What that tells us is that you have debt falling off, and we can recapture that debt service to be used for new projects, therefore keeping the smooth debt service that we really want to see in order to keep the finance folks happy.

531
00:54:31,402 --> 00:54:34,864
And then funded via PAYGO is also listed there.

532
00:54:34,884 --> 00:54:36,505
Again, we have no PAYGO committed.

533
00:54:38,408 --> 00:54:42,956
So then moving down to the last table, we can see it's titled target capital investment.

534
00:54:43,017 --> 00:54:50,130
So this is where we identify what the resources are that we want to commit.

535
00:54:53,595 --> 00:54:56,556
So the first line says debt service at 3% of net budget.

536
00:54:57,157 --> 00:55:03,760
What I'm doing there is taking the net budget that I'm projecting and figuring out what 3% of that would be.

537
00:55:04,380 --> 00:55:13,004
And that is going to be compared to our existing debt service to generate the amount of money we have available for new debt, which is that next line you see.

538
00:55:13,604 --> 00:55:19,567
So looking to FY24, under the line that says available for new debt, there's $564,000 available for new debt service.

539
00:55:22,768 --> 00:55:26,329
You can see it grows as the years go on.

540
00:55:27,289 --> 00:55:33,371
Now $564,000 for debt service, that doesn't mean you can only do a project that's $500,000.

541
00:55:33,952 --> 00:55:35,292
It means the debt service would be $500,000.

542
00:55:36,833 --> 00:55:41,314
So you can do exponentially more in terms of the issuances, the total project cost.

543
00:55:43,309 --> 00:55:48,193
Down at the bottom, you can see the free cash investment target and the ARPA investment target.

544
00:55:48,813 --> 00:55:56,940
So these numbers were developed in conversations with the mayor and her team and the finance team.

545
00:55:57,480 --> 00:56:03,045
And so we've got 1.5 million from free cash in FY23.

546
00:56:05,147 --> 00:56:08,169
1.5 million in free cash in FY24.

547
00:56:09,009 --> 00:56:15,214
And then we're going to drop down because we are not sure whether free cash numbers are going to continue to be as strong.

548
00:56:16,354 --> 00:56:22,679
So we drop down to 750,000 and then inch our way back up, as you can see here in the table.

549
00:56:24,243 --> 00:56:24,583
ARPA.

550
00:56:24,604 --> 00:56:27,246
Oh, and one note about the free cash investment.

551
00:56:27,307 --> 00:56:32,753
So that amount is not inclusive of the $2.9 million that's already been appropriated.

552
00:56:32,833 --> 00:56:34,855
That you'll see up at the top of the chart.

553
00:56:36,297 --> 00:56:36,837
And then ARPA.

554
00:56:38,884 --> 00:56:44,425
is limited to 23, 24, 25 because of those deadlines that the federal government included.

555
00:56:45,065 --> 00:56:49,086
So we've got that $10.4 million number in FY23.

556
00:56:49,746 --> 00:56:57,628
That includes the $9.9 million that has already been identified and approved for ARPA funds for capital projects.

557
00:56:58,068 --> 00:57:00,989
Not all of those projects have been started by department heads.

558
00:57:03,069 --> 00:57:21,695
um you know those that can take time procurement of vehicles etc can take time but it's already been committed through the process that the city's developed so that um so really what we're talking about in terms of new ARPA spending for FY23 there's a half a million dollars which i think is all dedicated to road work

559
00:57:23,187 --> 00:57:23,707
in the plan.

560
00:57:24,148 --> 00:57:29,930
And then in 24 and 25, we have a million dollars that we're saying is our target spending.

561
00:57:30,310 --> 00:57:37,733
So in total, that bottom line there tells us how much money we have for cash capital or PAYGO capital.

562
00:57:40,674 --> 00:57:43,815
I just wanna mention, I see a notification that there's someone in the waiting room.

563
00:57:43,895 --> 00:57:45,356
I don't know if you all are seeing that.

564
00:57:47,347 --> 00:57:47,687
Thank you.

565
00:57:50,231 --> 00:57:50,732
Thank you.

566
00:57:51,633 --> 00:57:55,859
Do you know if we're figuring in the school reimbursement in this plan.

567
00:58:01,562 --> 00:58:05,626
some MSBA monies.

568
00:58:06,166 --> 00:58:19,898
There is a project for roof work district-wide, and I believe the total was $8.4 million, so it's spread across multiple school buildings, and we estimated a 50% MSBA portion.

569
00:58:20,438 --> 00:58:23,481
So that is one spot where we did use MSBA

570
00:58:25,147 --> 00:58:36,337
We did not yet include MSBA monies for the high school project, because my understanding is that there's still

571
00:58:38,116 --> 00:58:44,037
some work being done around what that project is going to be, and we're still waiting to hear from MSBA.

572
00:58:44,077 --> 00:59:01,180
So we took a conservative approach and did not include MSBA monies, but obviously that's something that would be wonderful to have and would significantly improve the finances, especially when it comes to that major building project at the high school.

573
00:59:07,966 --> 00:59:08,406
Thank you.

574
00:59:09,667 --> 00:59:10,227
Just a question.

575
00:59:10,247 --> 00:59:11,348
I really like targets.

576
00:59:11,388 --> 00:59:12,729
I think targets are super helpful.

577
00:59:12,749 --> 00:59:19,652
So I like seeing that our target for capital investment is that our debt services stick around at 3% of our net general fund budget.

578
00:59:21,253 --> 00:59:27,957
My question is, is it, you know, the free cash target, obviously the ARPA target is, is short run.

579
00:59:28,057 --> 00:59:32,179
So, you know, that money's going away, but the free cash target, it seems ad hoc.

580
00:59:32,199 --> 00:59:37,362
And I heard you say, you know, we're not sure 2025, fiscal 25 free cash is going to be as strong, et cetera.

581
00:59:38,192 --> 00:59:59,524
Do you think it's possible to set like a percentage target for how much of free cash we should be allocating towards capital expenditures every year, rather than just kind of saying, well we think free cash isn't going to be great so we'll use 750,000 or is that just not something that you guys do have seen in other communities.

582
01:00:04,051 --> 01:00:07,453
It is something that some communities do.

583
01:00:08,714 --> 01:00:22,082
What I have seen in terms of financial policies around free cash use is something along the lines of, we are going to appropriate no less than 25% of free cash into a capital stabilization fund.

584
01:00:22,802 --> 01:00:28,664
We are going to appropriate no less than 25% of free cash into a general stabilization fund.

585
01:00:29,144 --> 01:00:37,868
And then the rest is left to be available for various uses that the city should decide upon.

586
01:00:38,548 --> 01:00:46,891
So that is actually a really appropriate approach.

587
01:00:47,151 --> 01:00:49,232
Setting a free cash dollar target

588
01:00:52,440 --> 01:01:02,127
is one way to do it, but using a capital stabilization fund and committing to a percentage of free cash allows you to be flexible.

589
01:01:02,187 --> 01:01:10,514
So you don't know if your free cash is gonna come in up here or down here, but no matter where it comes in, you're committing a certain percentage of that right to your capital stabilization fund.

590
01:01:10,594 --> 01:01:16,118
And that capital stabilization fund then becomes the source of pay-go capital.

591
01:01:16,778 --> 01:01:37,811
So rather than using free cash directly, you have it sort of passed through the capital stabilization fund in a way that gives you consistent funding for capital, commits the city or town by policy to funding that, and it just kind of creates a more consistent resource for cash capital.

592
01:01:38,051 --> 01:01:41,894
So it's something that I would absolutely recommend the city consider.

593
01:01:43,641 --> 01:01:44,722
Yeah, that's really helpful.

594
01:01:44,742 --> 01:01:54,427
I think that's the way we need to, or you know that direction is a direction we really should move in because I think it helps for planning purposes and, you know, we say free cash and Councilor Carvio was talking about it last night.

